  "text": "The hydrogen-bonding interaction between the ligand (Pt complex) and DNA is best structurally characterized by the formation of phosphate clamps ( Figure 3 ). In the phosphate clamp, a single OP atom accepts two hydrogen bonds, one from each of two adjacent a(m)mino groups of a PtN 4 unit. Three phosphate clamps involving two PtN 4 coordination spheres of TriplatinNC-A are evident in the electron density. In the case of 2, seven phosphate clamps involving four Pt 2+ centers were observed [CITATION_1] . Similar to the previous structure, 1 forms an extensive hydrogen bonding and electrostatic network within the DDD crystal, bridging a total of five different symmetry-related duplexes ( Figure 3 ).",
